The compilation process in C involves four main steps:
1. Preprocessing : This is the first phase through which the source code is passed.
The preprocessor takes care of the `#include` directives, macro expansions, conditional compilation instructions and other preprocessing directives.
The output of this step is an expanded source code file.
2. Compiling : The expanded source code from the preprocessing step is then compiled.
The compiler checks the syntax of the program, performs semantic analysis, and translates the C code into assembly code.
3. Assembling : The assembly code is then converted into machine code (object code).
This step involves translating the assembly instructions into binary machine code instructions.
4. Linking : Finally, the linker takes one or more object files and combines them into a single executable file.
It also links any library functions used in the program.
After these steps, you can run the obtained executable file to see the output on your screen.
